With the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant accident at TEPCO, discussions aimed at full-scale operation of test operations off the coast of Fukushima Prefecture were put into practice in each district.
Mr. Tetsu Nozaki, President of the Federation of Fisheries Cooperatives, said, "As the Federation of Fisheries Cooperatives in the prefecture, we need a flow toward full-scale operation, and we want to gather representatives and start discussions."
The Union Presidents' Association also approved the formal addition of the fish species to the target fish species for test operations in the areas of Casago, Sakura Mas and Murasoi off the coast of Fukushima Prefecture where restrictions on shipment were lifted.
The remaining undisclosed marine products were two fish species, Vinosgai and Common Cusbe.
After the end of the operation, President Nozaki responded to the press coverage and stressed that the start of full-scale operation was not fixed.
Regarding the treatment water after purifying contaminated water at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant, Mr. Yoshiaki Harada, Minister of the Environment, and Mayor Ichiro Matsui, Mayor of Osaka City, said, "There is a problem with the Keren-tasting argument, and the position of opposition to ocean release remains unchanged."
When discussing full-scale operations, Akira Egawa, head of Iwaki City Fisheries Cooperative, pointed out that "it is necessary to suck up opinions from the bottom," and said that he respects the intentions of the members.
The Board of Directors meets with a group of affiliated branches to resolve the problems they face, and concludes as a city fishing cooperative.
