[Kyodo Shokudo, Koshiyama Wakamizu] A circle of "Kododo Shokudo" (Children's Cafeteria) that provides free or inexpensive meals for children is spreading nationwide.
According to research conducted by NPOs and other organizations, there are approximately 3,700 locations nationwide this year.
The number increased by one to six times compared to 2018, and there were 24 locations in Fukui Prefecture, which increased by nine compared to last year.
why is it now?
Makoto Yuasa, chairman of the Kyoto NPO and social activist, spoke about the background and significance of the lecture held in Sakai City.
Due to the declining birthrate and aging population, the area became lonely, and shopping streets declined.
There was no place for people to meet.
And he said, "We needed a place where people could interact with each other.
Even though it is called the Kyoto Children's Cafeteria, it is a place of multi-generational exchange where elderly people also participate.
It not only eliminates eating alone, but also helps raise children and improves the health of the elderly.
They cut off the chain of poverty and revitalize the region.
what's important is not to create children from there.
There are various places to offer meals every day from January 1 to May 1.
There are a wide variety of venues, from several to hundreds, from private homes to temples.
It is becoming an atmosphere that people who want to do can do.
The low threshold is attractive.
However, it is difficult to manage and secure staff.
sometimes we hear issues like a secure management system
"Connecting with society will become a safety net in case of disasters," says Yuasa.
It seems like the light of hope in closed society.
