Tokaimura Critical Accident, 20 years in 30 days, 300 nuclear facility troubles: Hokkaido Shimbun
From the next year of the critical accident in Tokai-mura, Ibaraki Prefecture, which was the first in the history of nuclear power in Japan, between 2000 and 2006, there were 336 reports of accidents and failures at nuclear facilities nationwide.
20 years in 30 days from the critical accident that alarmed the safety myth of the nuclear industry.
According to the report, although the International Assessment Scale (INES), which shows seriousness, accounted for about 90% of items that were not evaluated and not considered safe, it is necessary to raise safety awareness on the basis of lessons learned from the accident and the accident at TEPCO's Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant in 11 years.
Mitsukazu Soda, who has completed the story and original drawings of creative picture books, is seeking donations for publication.
Koichi Soda (64), an artist from the Echizen City Regional Development Cooperation Team in Fukui Prefecture, started a crowdfunding campaign aimed at publishing creative picture books inspired by legends in Fukui Prefecture.
Mr. Soda, who was originally from Hokkaido and started his activities as a member of the cooperative group in April this year, said, "I want to convey the kindness of Fukui people based on deep faith through picture books."
[Donation is here] To convey Fukui's heart.
While Mr. Soda is active as an artist working on contemporary art based on mathematics, he has also been active as a member of the cooperative team since the end of the calendar.
After working on the town development of Nagano, Kumamoto and Tochigi, he joined Echizen City in April this year.
In the same city that produced Riko Kako and Chihiro Iwasaki, he aims to create a town that makes use of picture books.
Soda lived in the city and said, "I was surprised by the depth of compassion around me for the first time."
What attracted attention was the legend of the city of Awara, 'The face of the demon of the bride'.
It is a story that a heart-friendly bride continues to chant Nenbutsu (Buddhist invocation) to help her mother without worrying about the fact that she was surprised by her face.
"I forgot my hatred and returned with kindness and kindness, and I felt the origin of the faith and kindness of the people of Fukui."
Inspired by the original picture book, Soda went to Yoshizaki Gobo in Awara City as soon as he arrived, and made the story "Meoto Oni" that a loving couple and a boy appear.
From June, he drew 10 scenes with warm watercolors, taking advantage of his job, and the materials of picture books were scattered.
In addition, Echizen Washi, a traditional craft that lives in Echizen City, will be used to cover picture books with washi.
This leads to an opportunity for parents and children to enjoy the touch of Japanese paper through reading and listening.
The goal of the donation amount is 850,000 yen for 600 copies.
The deadline is 25 October.
Mr. Soda said, "Fukui's heart, which has been nurtured under the historical Buddhist culture, is proud throughout Japan.
I want to convey the true kindness and compassion that has been handed down to children through picture books."
Fukui Prefecture is one of the projects in which Fukui Prefecture certifies 11 projects for regional revitalization that are challenged by local cooperatives and businesses in the prefecture, and supports them by utilizing hometown tax.
The Fukui Shimbun provides information and the Fukui Bank cooperates with management support.
Donations can be made from the crowdfunding website "Redifor."
