Sakura shrimp during the growth process PT such as Shizuoka City, depth 290 meters taken | Shizuoka Shimbun at Ess
Sakura Ebi, born this year, has been successfully photographed in the deep sea of Suruga Bay.
The Yuhi Sakura Ebi Project, a project of the Ocean Industry Cluster Council led by industry, academia, and government officials in Shizuoka City, succeeded in photographing sakura shrimp, which is thought to have been born during the spawning season this spring and summer, at a depth of 290 meters in Suruga Bay.
The video of the growth process is valuable, and the concerned parties want to lead to the elucidation of the ecology of sakura shrimp, which has many mysteries.
The photo was taken near the bottom of the sea about 1 to 5 km off the coast of Kamahara district, Shimizu Ward, the city.
A total of 300 were confirmed in 17 minutes.
During the day, the traditional knowledge that sakura shrimp in the deep sea form a certain group at the bottom of the sea was reaffirmed.
The adult body is about 40 mm long, and the individual reflected is about 23 mm long.
The spawning period was identified by matching the seasonal data of the freshly caught sakura shrimp.
Detailed analysis is requested by Fujitsu Software Technologies and Shizuoka College of Technology, which make up the team.
Keisuke Mizuno, Project Leader, said, "I want to capture the living figure of individuals in the growth process, including fry."
